<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-06-30T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-06-30T07:00:00-05:00" n="146" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d146">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">851.4061 Motion Pictures/169:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France (<persName type="from">Armour</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-30T13:00:00+01:00">June 30, 1932—1
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 30—9 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>403. Your 236, June 29, 8 p.m. Vigorous informal protests were made
                                this morning which it is hoped will result either in the indefinite
                                postponement of the prohibitive motion picture film quota or a more
                                favorable position for American films.</p>
                            <closer><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">Armour</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>